# Please use the following smoke test to verify the basic functionality of nano.
# In many terminals, Meta commands can be entered either with Alt+<key> or by
# pressing Esc and then the key.
#
# Confirm the correct nano is installed
$ nano -V

# Go to a testing directory and create a small sample file.
$ mkdir -p /tmp/nano-smoke && cd /tmp/nano-smoke
$ printf '%s\n' 'first line' 'second line' 'third line' > sample.txt

# 1. Create and save a new file.
$ nano new_file
# Type a few lines of text.
# Press Ctrl+O, then Enter, to save the file.
# Observe that nano reports that the file was written.
# Press Ctrl+X to exit.
# Observe that you return to the shell and that 'new_file' exists.

# 2. Reopen the file and exercise basic editing.
$ nano new_file
# Move with the arrow keys and edit the text.
# Press M-A to start marking text, move the cursor, then press M-6 to copy it.
# Press Ctrl+U to paste the copied text.
# Press Ctrl+K to cut the current line or the marked text.
# Observe that copy, paste, and cut behave as expected.
# Press Ctrl+O, then Enter, to save. Press Ctrl+X to exit.

# 3. Open an existing file on a specific line and column.
$ nano +2,1 sample.txt
# Observe that the cursor starts on line 2, column 1.
# Press Ctrl+W, type 'third', and press Enter.
# Observe that nano jumps to the matching text.
# Press Ctrl+X

# 4. Exercise search and replace.
$ nano sample.txt
# Press Ctrl+\ to start replace, type 'third', press Enter, then type 'THIRD'
# and press Enter.
# When prompted, press Y to replace the match.
# Observe that the text is replaced.
